<p class="bold">This paintframe is one of a handful remaining in the UK – and very few of those are operational, let alone located in the theatre itself. </p>
<p>Terry Hands, who was Artistic Director here from the 1990s to the mid 2010s, had a lot to do with Theatr Clwyd’s paintframe staying on site – </p>
 <</append>>
<</timed>>
<<timed 20s>>
   <<append "#msgMount">>
<div class="quote"><p>“The biggest legacy that Terry left was that we had all of the making departments in-house. He fought tooth and nail. It’s one of our USPs – and that it's one of very few theatres in the in the UK, and yet we're outside a small market town in North East Wales, and we've got all of...that!”</p></div>
 <</append>>
<</timed>>
<<timed 34s>>
   <<append "#msgMount">>
<p>That’s Liam Evans-Ford, who became Executive Director at Theatr Clwyd in 2016. He’s someone who, like Terry Hands, has fought tooth and nail for the theatre and particularly the building’s redevelopment.</p>

<p>There’s been a history of battlers at Theatr Clwyd. But this stuff is important. An on-site workshop means the theatre can employ people locally, to build an incredible crew, who make sets right here, which is such a privilege. </p>
